446.overview:
What is celiac disease?&nbsp;

Celiac disease is an autoimmune disorder that can occur in genetically predisposed individuals, in whom the ingestion of gluten proteins present in wheat, barley, and rye or derivatives, causes damage to the villi of the small intestine.&nbsp;&nbsp;

It is estimated that 1% of the general population develops celiac disease. In Europe, the prevalence of celiac disease varies from 2% in Finland to 0.3% in Germany. All epidemiological studies indicate that celiac disease is more prevalent in women, with a female to male ratio of 2:1. &nbsp;

Celiac disease can be diagnosed at any age. In children, diarrhea and malabsorption syndrome predominate. In adults, 75% of cases are diagnosed in women, with a peak incidence in the third decade and atypical symptoms, represented by iron deficiency anemia and prolonged non-specific discomfort.&nbsp;

Causes of celiac disease&nbsp;

Celiac disease is caused by an abnormal response to gluten. Gluten is partially digested in the intestine and the peptides produced, such as gliadin, can cause an inflammatory response in susceptible individuals. The abnormally triggered immune response to gluten causes pathological lesions in the intestinal epithelium, altering the structure of the intestinal villi and their main function, which is the absorption of nutrients.&nbsp;

The role of genetics in celiac disease predisposition&nbsp;

SNPs have been described that are predictive of HLA risk factors associated with CD). Our team of geneticists evaluates the rs2187668 and rs7454108 polymorphisms that are associated with the presence of the HLA-DQ2.5 and HLA-DQ8 haplogroups, respectively.&nbsp;

CD patients have at least one copy of HLA-DQ2.5 and HLA-DQ8. Therefore, the absence of HLA-DQ2.5 and HLA-DQ8 haplotypes leads to the conclusion that the patient is not at risk of developing celiac disease. The accuracy of its predictive value is very high, around 99%.&nbsp;

Prevention and treatment&nbsp;

The only effective treatment is adherence to a life-long gluten-free diet, for symptomatic as well as asymptomatic patients. A strict gluten-free dietary regimen leads to the disappearance of the clinical symptoms and functional alterations, as well as to the normalization of the intestinal lining. If a gluten-free diet is strictly followed, it has been shown that after 10 years the risk of developing neoplastic diseases and probably autoimmune illnesses is&nbsp;similar to&nbsp;that of the general population.&nbsp;

446.technical_description:
Celiac disease (CD) is an autoimmune condition characterized by inflammation of the intestinal mucosa as a consequence of a reaction to gluten ingestion. It is characterized by a variable combination of gluten-dependent clinical manifestations, the presence of specific antibodies, and a genetic predisposition mediated largely by the presence of HLA DQ2 and HLA DQ8 haplotypes.&nbsp;

Among the main CD clinical symptoms are included persistent unexplained&nbsp;abdominal pain, prolonged fatigue, unexpected weight loss, mouth ulcers, deficiency in iron, vitamin B12, and folate, and osteoporosis (Lebwohl&nbsp;et al., 2018).&nbsp;

Gluten is the term for the storage proteins of the cereal grains wheat, rye, and barley. Gluten proteins are incompletely digested, and large peptides pass through the epithelial barrier of the intestine and gliadin which is a peptide that forms part of gluten can interact with HLA DQ2 or DQ8 molecules on specific immune cells (antigen-presenting cells) triggering the release of inflammatory molecules that can contribute to CD development.&nbsp;

There are cases of patients that show non-celiac gluten sensitivity and have symptoms after gluten ingestion as abdominal pain, bloating, diarrhea, constipation, headache, fatigue, dermatitis, among others. The symptoms disappear with gluten withdrawal, and they experience relapse if gluten is reintroduced. Unfortunately, the underlying biological mechanisms of non-celiac gluten sensitivity and biomarkers remain unknown (Lebwohl et al., 2015).&nbsp;

HLA&nbsp;gene and celiac disease&nbsp;

The intestinal epithelial damage associated with CD results from the presentation of gliadin peptide fragments by antigen-presenting cells through HLA proteins that are on this cell's surface. The different HLA haplotypes encode proteins with affinities for specific antigens. The haplotypes DQ2 and DQ8 allow for the presentation of gluten antigens by antigen-presenting cells, which can result in activation of an immune response and development of celiac disease (Lebwohl et al., 2021).&nbsp;

The HLA-heterodimers, named DQ2 (encoded by DQA1*05 and DQB1*02 alleles) and DQ8 (encoded by DQA1*03 and DQB1*0302 alleles) confer an important susceptibility to the condition development (Caio et al., 2019). The presence of these heterodimers is estimated to increase the risk of developing CD by 25-30% (Liu et al., 2014). Furthermore, HLA is not the unique genetic factor related to CD risk, it has been described more than 39 non-HLA genes that can also contribute. &nbsp;

The terms HLA-DQ2 and HLA-DQ8 identify the alpha chain of the HLA heterodimer. Four heterodimers confer susceptibility to the development of CD, but only the two named above are considered risk CD factors (Sollid et al., 1993). &nbsp;

The HLA-DQ2 molecule may be encoded by A1*0501/B1*0201 (DQ2.5) or A1*0201/B1*0201 (DQ2.2) alleles. Multiple scientific studies have determined that, in the European population, 90-95% of celiac patients have the DQ2.5 variant.&nbsp;

On the other hand,&nbsp;most&nbsp;DQ2-negative celiac patients have the HLA-DQ8 heterodimer which, in addition to celiac disease, has been associated with type 1 diabetes.&nbsp;

The presence of serological markers together with a Marsh II or Marsh III lesion (Marsh score scale is a categorization of the intestinal tissue histologic characteristics that helps clinicians during CD diagnose) are sufficient to propose a diagnosis and HLA-DQ haplotype genotyping has a secondary role. Although HLA-DQ haplotype genotyping cannot be used for diagnosing, it has a strong negative predictive value, being useful to rule out the disease in patients with a confusing diagnosis (Hills et al., 2005).&nbsp;

Tag SNPs have been described that allow the prediction of HLA risk factors associated with CD (Monsuur et al., 2008). Here are evaluated the rs2187668 and rs7454108 polymorphisms that are associated with the presence of the HLA-DQ2.5 and HLA-DQ8 haplogroups, respectively.&nbsp;

It should be noted that patients with&nbsp;CD&nbsp;have at least one copy of the HLA-DQ2.5 and HLA-DQ8.&nbsp;Therefore, the absence of HLA-DQ2.5 and HLA-DQ8 haplotypes leads to the conclusion that&nbsp;the patient is not&nbsp;at risk of developing celiac disease. The accuracy of its predictive value is 99%.&nbsp;

The HLA-DQ2.5 and HLA-DQ8 test can exclude the patients that are not at risk of developing CD but cannot confirm the presence of celiac disease. For diagnostic purposes, other tests must be performed as serological tests, endoscopies, and intestinal biopsies.&nbsp;

