448.technical_description:
CD36&nbsp;gene&nbsp;

Cluster determinant 36 (CD36) is a membrane glycoprotein involved in a wide range of functions in different cell types, with a prominent role in the coordination of cellular events involved in fatty acid (FA) uptake and processing. Thus, CD36 expressed on intestinal enterocytes interacts with dietary fatty acids released from triglyceride digestion, facilitating fatty acid uptake and chylomicron assembly. In addition, it promotes cell adhesion&nbsp;and&nbsp;contributes directly or indirectly to vitamin E transport and internalization.&nbsp;&nbsp;

The Healthy Lifestyle in Europe by Nutrition in Adolescence (HELENA) study studied the polymorphism located in the intron region of the CD36 gene (rs1761667), which has been associated with lower expression of the CD36 transcript and identified that individuals homozygous for the G allele had a lower plasma&nbsp;alfa-tocopherol concentration (3%) (Galm&eacute;s&nbsp;et al., 2018).&nbsp;

SCARB1 gene&nbsp;

Scavenger receptor class B member 1 (SR-B1) is encoded by the SCARB1&nbsp;gene and&nbsp;is a membrane receptor that is widely expressed in many&nbsp;mammalians&nbsp;cell types. The protein acts as a plasma membrane receptor for high-density lipoprotein (HDL) cholesterol and mediates cholesterol transfer to and from HDL.&nbsp;

With respect to vitamin E, SR-B1 is involved in the uptake of the major forms of VE from the diet; it participates in its transport from the enterocytes into the blood, in the uptake of VE-HDL vitamin complexes by the different receptor tissues, and in the excretion of&nbsp;alfa-tocopherol with biliary secretion.&nbsp;

Several studies have identified different polymorphisms produced in this gene associated with circulating concentrations of alpha-tocopherol, increasing serum vitamin E levels depending on the presence of the minor or risk allele for the rs11057830 polymorphism (Major et al., 2011).&nbsp;

On the other hand, the rs5888 polymorphism, also known as A350A, is a variant located in exon 8 of the SCARB1 gene that includes the exchange of the minor allele (G) for (A). It has been significantly seen that TT carriers have the lowest plasma alfa-tocopherol levels compared to CC or CT carriers and CT carriers have shown the highest levels compared to the other two counterparts (Niforou et al., 2020).&nbsp;

TTPA gene&nbsp;

The alfa-tocopherol transfer protein (alfaTTP) is a cytosolic protein encoded by the TTPA gene. It is highly expressed in the liver where it binds alfa-tocopherol with high selectivity and affinity. This protein plays an important role in the regulation of alfa-tocopherol storage in the liver and its transport between membrane vesicles, facilitating the packaging of EV into VLDLs, its secretion from hepatocytes, and its delivery to tissues outside the liver.&nbsp;

According to the study carried out in men by Margaret Wright, the rs6994076 (980T>A) polymorphism in the promoter region of the gene affects alpha-tocopherol concentrations as well as the response to dietary vitamin E supplementation. According to this study, carriers of both copies of the T allele variant had 3% less a-tocopherol than those with both copies of the A allele (Wright et al., 2009).&nbsp;

CYP4F2 gene&nbsp;&nbsp;

Involved in the metabolism of several endogenous substrates, including fatty acids,&nbsp;eicosanoids,&nbsp;and vitamins. CYP4F2 contributes to vitamin E metabolism by catalyzing the oxidation of the tocopherol side chain.&nbsp;&nbsp;

The study conducted by Major J.M determined that those individuals had higher serum alpha-tocopherol levels in proportion to the number of the minor (T) allele they carried, for the rs2108622 polymorphism (Major et al., 2011).&nbsp;

ZPR1 gene&nbsp;&nbsp;

Acts as a signaling molecule that communicates proliferative growth signals from the cytoplasm to the nucleus. Among other functions, it helps to activate other genes (transcription factors) involved in the use of vitamin E in the body.&nbsp;

The study carried out by Major J.M determined that those individuals had higher serum levels of alpha-tocopherol in proportion to the number of minor alleles (G) they carried, for the rs964184 polymorphism (Major et al., 2011).&nbsp;

rs12272004&nbsp;

Of the SNPs associated with&nbsp;alfa-tocopherol levels, rs12272004 is located on chromosome 11, near the APOA5 gene. Major J.M determined that the A allele of rs12272004 was strongly and consistently associated with higher plasma&nbsp;alfa-tocopherol levels (Major et al., 2011).&nbsp;

